*Assessment*

While testing EUCA-10993, based upon the [AWS ELB documentation (API Version 2012-06-01)|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ElasticLoadBalancing/latest/DeveloperGuide/UsingIAM.html], when using a defined {{Resource}} element in an IAM policy for ELB (i.e. not the wildcard {{*}}), the following ELB API actions should return an error:

* DescribeInstanceHealth
* DescribeLoadBalancerAttributes
* DescribeLoadBalancerPolicyTypes
* DescribeLoadBalancers
* DescribeLoadBalancerPolicies
* DescribeTags

Per AWS documentation:
{quote}
If you specify a resource with an API action that does not support resource-level permissions, the API call fails. Instead, you must use the following resource statement with API actions that don't support resource-level permissions:

{code}"Resource": "*"{code}
{quote}

An example on AWS:
{code}
## IAM policy applied to 'hasp' user ##
$ cat euca10993-elasticloadbalancing-policy.json
{
    "Version":"2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": "elasticloadbalancing:*",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:elasticloadbalancing:*:*:loadbalancer/*"
        }
    ]
}

$ aws elb describe-load-balancers --profile hasp-personal

A client error (AccessDenied) occurred when calling the DescribeLoadBalancers operation: User: arn:aws:iam::986451091583:user/hasp is not authorized to perform: elasticloadbalancing:DescribeLoadBalancers
{code}

On Eucalyptus 4.2, this isn't the case.  When using a defined {{Resource}} element in the IAM access policy, any of the unsupported API actions returned successful responses.
{code}
[root@h-08 ~]# euare-grouplistpolicies -g admins --region devops-admin@asap-rocky-2015 -v
elb-access
{
    "Version":"2012-10-17",
